INRTODUCTION

Overview

The english premier league 2019/20 season was 29 games in when it was abruptly cut short by the covid-19 pandemic. Although some would say that by this time the tittle holder was already known and that handing over the cup was the only thing left , there was still much to play for.The top 4 spots and relegation battle were really interesting.

We will work with the data that we have and visualize some statistics throughout the season.

Objectives

We will answer some few questions like

  1. Does home vs away really matter?

Outcome

Home advantage is real mainly due to the home crowd.

Basically let us have fun with the data.

Load in the libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(corrplot)

DATA CLEANING

We check for missing variables.

Missing_Indices<-sapply(epl, function(x)sum(is.na(x)))
Missing_Summary<-data.frame(Index=names(epl), Missing_Values=Missing_Indices)
Missing_Summary[Missing_Summary$Missing_Values>0,]

There are no missing variables.

DATA EXPLORATION.

WHO WON THE EPL 19/20 SEASON

Let us show the table of the results.

epl.table<-epl %>% 
  group_by(teamId) %>% 
  summarise(Played=n(),
            Points=sum(pts),
            Goals.For=sum(scored),
            Goals.Against=sum(missed),
            Goal.Difference=(Goals.For -Goals.Against)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(Points))

epl.table

If the season were to end,

The winners - Liverpool

Relegation - Norwich , West Ham and Aston Villa

Let us compare Liverpool and Norwich seasons.

LIVERPOOL

Let us take a look at the stats of the premier league holders.

Liverpool<-epl %>% 
  filter(teamId=="Liverpool") %>% 
  group_by(h_a) %>% 
  summarise(played=n(),
            avg_xg=mean(xG),
            avg_axg=mean(xGA),
            tot_scored=sum(scored),
            tot_conceeded=sum(missed),
            avg_ppda=mean(ppda_cal),
            avg_ppdaA=mean(allowed_ppda),
            avg_deep=mean(deep),
            avg_deepA=mean(deep_allowed))

gather_Liverpool<-gather(Liverpool, key="var", value="val", -h_a)


gather_Liverpool[c(3:6, 11:18),] %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=var, y=val, fill=h_a)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  labs(title="Liverpool Home and Away",
       fill = "Home-Away")

Their average xG is sligher higher at home. When they are away the opposition is expected to score more goals looking at the axG. Funny enough they allow more opponents in their final third when they are home .Average PPDA is lower at home meaning they manage to press their opponents better at home.

NORWICH

Let us look at the stats of the team bottom of the table.

Norwich<-epl %>% 
  filter(teamId=="Norwich") %>% 
  group_by(h_a) %>% 
  summarise(played=n(),
            avg_xg=mean(xG),
            avg_axg=mean(xGA),
            tot_scored=sum(scored),
            tot_conceeded=sum(missed),
            avg_ppda=mean(ppda_cal),
            avg_ppdaA=mean(allowed_ppda),
            avg_deep=mean(deep),
            avg_deepA=mean(deep_allowed))

gather_Norwich<-gather(Norwich, key="var", value="val", -h_a)


gather_Liverpool[c(3:6, 11:18),] %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=var, y=val, fill=h_a)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  labs(title="Norwich Home and Away",
       fill="Home-Away")

Their average deepA is higher at home meaning they let more opposition in their final third when at home hence they are dominated at home more.This can be attributed to the fact that they sit back and defend deep.Generally they have a very low xG hence scoring very few goals.

GOALS

Our favourite part of the game, goals.

We want to find out which factors affect number of goals scored in a game,which team scored the most goals, which half had the most goals scored...


Correlaion
First of all we identify the numeric variables.

numericVars<-which(sapply(epl, is.numeric)) #Index vector for numeric variables.
numericVarsNames<-names(numericVars) #name vectors for numeric variables.

Now we find their correlation.

epl_numVar<-epl[,numericVars]
cor_numVar<-cor(epl_numVar, use="pairwise.complete.obs") 

#sort on decreasing correlation with goals.
cor_sorted<-as.matrix(sort(cor_numVar[,"tot_goal"],decreasing = TRUE))

#select only high correlations.
corHigh<-names(which(apply(cor_sorted,1 , function(x)abs(x)>0.5)))
cor_numVar<-cor_numVar[corHigh,corHigh]

heat <-epl_numVar

library(reshape2)

qplot(x=Var1, y=Var2, data = melt(cor(cor_numVar, use="p")), fill=value, geom="tile") +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low="green", high="red", mid="white", midpoint=0, limit=c(-1,1), space = "lab", name="Correlation") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=45, vjust=1, size=8, hjust=1)) +
  coord_fixed() +
  ggtitle("Correlation Heatmap") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.4))

Total goals has a high correlation(0.98) with Total points .The more goals you score the higher your chance of winning the match.

Total goals conceeded has a high correlation(0.78) with the round. If you are away you have a higher chance of conceeding more goals.

Which team had the most goals

epl %>% 
  group_by(teamId) %>% 
  summarise(goals_for=sum(scored),
            goals_against=sum(missed),
            difference=(goals_for - goals_against)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(difference))

Liverpool had the highest goal difference of 45 while Norwich had the lowest of -27

epl.table %>% 
  mutate(teamId = fct_reorder(teamId, Goals.For)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=Goals.For, y=teamId)) +
  geom_col(fill="darkorange") +
  labs(x="Goals scored",
       y="Team",
       title="Goals scored by the differnt teams")

As shown above, the difference between the goals scored by the top and bottom team is large(over 40 goals). This can be attributed to quality of players and style of play by different managers.Most teams are around the 30 - 40 mark.

MATCHDAY

Does matchday matter?

Match_days<-epl %>% 
  group_by(teamId ,matchDay) %>% 
  summarise(count=n())

Match_days %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=matchDay,y=count,fill=matchDay)) +
  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~ teamId) +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_blank())

Teams like Bournemouth, Brighton and Burnley played mostly on Saturdays meaning they had lots of time to prepare for their games but were still on the bottom half of the table.

Arsenal and Wolves had more spread out matchdays thus a hectic schedule but they performed relatively well on the table.

So we can conclude that Matchday does not matter as much but there are other external factors that contribute to perfoamnce such as participation in other competitions.

HOME VS AWAY

Home table

h_table<-epl %>% 
  filter(h_a =="h") %>% 
  group_by(teamId) %>% 
  arrange(teamId,date) %>% 
  summarise(played=n(),
            h_points=sum(pts),
            h_goals=sum(scored),
            h_con=sum(missed),
            goal_diff=h_goals - h_con,
            success_h=h_points/(played *3)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(h_points))

h_table

Away table

a_table<-epl %>% 
  filter(h_a=="a") %>% 
  group_by(teamId) %>% 
  arrange(teamId,date) %>% 
  summarise(played=n(),
            a_points=sum(pts),
            a_goals=sum(scored),
            a_con=sum(missed),
            goal_diff=a_goals - a_con,
            success_a=a_points/(played *3)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(a_points))

a_table

There are a couple of interesting things.

The last team on the home table has a success rate of 0.31 while the bottom team on the away table has a success rate of 0.13.

Newcastle , on the away table is 5th with the same success rate.

On the home table the highetst goal difference is 28 while on the away table it is 17

We can conclude that home advantage is real mainly due to the crowd.

Home vs Away success difference

successDiff<-inner_join(h_table[,c(1,7)], a_table[,c(1,7)]) #joing the home sucess and away colums grouped by team id.

successDiff %>% 
  mutate(diff=success_h - success_a) %>% 
  arrange(desc(diff))

Wolves, Chelsea and Southampton performed better away compared to home.

Everton had the best perfomance difference.

REFEREES

refs<-epl %>% 
  group_by(Referee.x) %>% 
  summarise(games=n()/2) %>% 
  arrange(desc(games))

refs

M Atkinsonn was the referee in most games(25). Some referees like S SCott and T Robinson had only one game each. They were probably junior referees.

head(refs, 10) %>% 
  mutate(Referee.x= fct_reorder(Referee.x, games)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=Referee.x, y=games, fill=Referee.x)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title="Referees game count")

M ATKINSON

Let us focus on the referee with the most game count. Which teams did he ref the most.

Atkn<-epl %>% 
  filter(Referee.x=="M Atkinson") %>% 
  group_by(teamId) %>% 
  summarise(games=n()) %>% 
  arrange(desc(games))

Atkn

He was the referee most number of times in Arsenal and Newcastle games, 5 each.

Atkn %>% 
  mutate(teamId = fct_reorder(teamId,games)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=teamId, y=games, fill=teamId)) +

  labs(title="Atkinson game count")

STRICTNESS OF THE REFEREES

Yellow cards

yellow_cards<-epl %>% 
  group_by(Referee.x) %>% 
  summarise(games=n(),
            total_yellow=sum(HY.x,AY.x),
            card_per_game=total_yellow/games) %>% 
  arrange(desc(card_per_game))

yellow_cards

P Bankes gave out the most yellow cards per game, approximately 5.

O Langford gave out 1 card per game.

Plotting the data.

yellow_cards %>% 
  mutate(Referee.x = fct_reorder(Referee.x, card_per_game)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=card_per_game, y=Referee.x, fill=Referee.x)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  labs(title="Referees count of yellow cards per game")

Red cards

red_cards<-epl %>% 
  group_by(Referee.x) %>% 
  summarise(games=n(),
            total_red=sum(HR.x,AR.x),
            card_per_game=total_red/games) %>% 
  arrange(desc(card_per_game))

red_cards

Red cards were issued sparingly with the highest G Scott with approximately 0.3 per game.

Plotting the data.

red_cards %>% 
  mutate(Referee.x = fct_reorder(Referee.x,card_per_game)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=card_per_game, y=Referee.x, fill=Referee.x)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  labs(title="Referees count of red cards per game")
